## What happened

In .NET 11, **DSA was removed from macOS**. Calling `DSA.Create()` (or any DSA signing/verification) now throws a `PlatformNotSupportedException` on macOS. Windows and Linux are unaffected.

## How to fix it

Since you need to **verify legacy DSA signatures**, you can't simply switch algorithms — the existing signatures were made with DSA. Your options:

1. **Skip DSA verification on macOS** if macOS doesn't need to verify legacy signatures:
   ```csharp
   if (!OperatingSystem.IsMacOS())
   {
       using var dsa = DSA.Create();
       // verify signature...
   }
   ```

2. **Use a cross-platform crypto library** (e.g., [BouncyCastle](https://www.nuget.org/packages/BouncyCastle.Cryptography)) that implements DSA in managed code, independent of the OS:
   ```csharp
   // With BouncyCastle — works on all platforms
   var dsaParams = new DsaPublicKeyParameters(y, new DsaParameters(p, q, g));
   var signer = SignerUtilities.GetSigner("SHA256withDSA");
   signer.Init(false, dsaParams);
   signer.BlockUpdate(data, 0, data.Length);
   bool valid = signer.VerifySignature(signature);
   ```

3. **Migrate signatures to ECDSA/RSA** long-term — re-sign existing data with a modern algorithm so you can drop the DSA dependency entirely.

**Recommendation:** For a verification-only scenario, option 2 (BouncyCastle) is the quickest path to keeping all three platforms working. Pair it with option 3 as a longer-term plan.
